## Field reference

| attribute | constraints |
|---|---|
| `name` | Required. 1-100 characters. Must be unique. |
| `description` | Optional. Up to 500 characters. |
| `scope_location_ids` | Optional. Set of location IDs (`int64`). |
| `permissions` | Optional. Set of permission names (see below). |

### `scope_location_ids`

`scope_location_ids` is the set of location IDs that scope the role: the role's
permissions apply only within those location subtrees. An **empty set or an
omitted attribute means the role is global** (applies to all locations). It is a
Set (order-independent); IDs must reference existing locations.

The superuser permission `*.*.*` **cannot** be combined with a non-empty
`scope_location_ids` — a superuser is global by definition. Setting both is
rejected by the server.

### `permissions`

`permissions` is the set of permission names assigned to the role. Names follow
the pattern `module.resource.action` (for example `app.tags.read`), plus the
single wildcard superuser permission `*.*.*`.

Permission names are **validated server-side**, not by a static enum in the
provider. The authoritative, always-current list of valid names is published by
the product itself through the [`mistershell_permissions`](../data-sources/permissions.md)
data source — query it for the live per-module enumeration. The provider does
not hardcode the list because permission names live in a server-side registry
that is not part of the published OpenAPI schema, so the on-product data source
is the single source of truth; an unknown name is surfaced as a server error.

#### Superuser rules

The `*.*.*` permission grants everything and is mutually exclusive:

- `*.*.*` **cannot** be combined with any other permission name.
- `*.*.*` **cannot** be used together with `scope_location_ids` (it is always
  global).
- No additional permission can be added to a role that already holds `*.*.*`.

All of these are enforced by the server and reported as an error on apply.

#### Permission modules

Every permission belongs to one of the following 27 modules (read live from
`GET /api/v1/permissions/modules`). Use a module name as the `module` filter on
the `mistershell_permissions` data source to list that module's permissions.

| module | covers |
|---|---|
| `system` | The superuser permission `*.*.*`. |
| `users` | Users and their details. |
| `roles` | Roles and permission assignment. |
| `permissions` | The permission registry (read-only). |
| `settings` | Application settings. |
| `auth_providers` | Authentication providers. |
| `backup` | Database backups. |
| `logs` | API and realtime logs. |
| `tasks` | Scheduled tasks. |
| `reports` | Generated reports. |
| `workers` | Workers. |
| `credentials` | Credentials. |
| `tags` | Tags and resource memberships. |
| `resources` | Network resources and their actions. |
| `session` | Session history, replays, and termination. |
| `commands` | Resource commands. |
| `notes` | Resource notes and attachments. |
| `motd` | Message-of-the-day entries. |
| `ai` | AI models, agents, prompts, chat, quick assist. |
| `metrics` | Health metric configurations. |
| `snapshots` | Immediate snapshot collection. |
| `snaps` | Config-snapshot element configurations. |
| `changelog` | Config changelog and diffs. |
| `automation` | Automation playbooks and runs. |
| `licenses` | Licenses. |
| `policy` | Session policy rules and ACLs. |
| `audit` | Security audit logs and log forwarding. |

To enumerate the exact permission names available on your instance:

```hcl
data "mistershell_permissions" "all" {}

output "permission_names" {
  value = [for p in data.mistershell_permissions.all.permissions : p.name]
}
```

